programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Former New Zealanders Brett and Rees are the proud parents of three young boys under the age of three and desperately need more space. But they love their inner-city Annandale community in Sydney, so their plan is to build on the small empty plot behind their home. Because the site is only six metres wide and hemmed in on three sides by buildings, two of them heritage listed, Brett and Rees are intent on maximising every last centimetre of space and light. Their tri-level design, with living and sleeping zones radiating off a glamorous, central indoor swimming pool, is a 21st-century re-imagining of the traditional terraced house. It takes five designs and three development applications before the local council finally approves the project, but that's not the end of their troubles. Barely has the first sod been turned when one of the heritage buildings on their boundary is in danger of collapsing because of the site excavations. Plus the narrow rear laneway is making access a nightmare for materials and machinery. To cap off their woes, Sydney experiences its wettest summer in 20 years. Exhausted and three months behind schedule, do Brett and Rees have enough grit and determination left in them to see their project through?(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Former New Zealanders Brett and Rees are the proud parents of three young boys under the age of three and desperately need more space. But they love their inner-city Annandale community in Sydney, so their plan is to build on the small empty plot behind their home. Because the site is only six metres wide and hemmed in on three sides by buildings, two of them heritage listed, Brett and Rees are intent on maximising every last centimetre of space and light. Their tri-level design, with living and sleeping zones radiating off a glamorous, central indoor swimming pool, is a 21st-century re-imagining of the traditional terraced house. It takes five designs and three development applications before the local council finally approves the project, but that's not the end of their troubles. Barely has the first sod been turned when one of the heritage buildings on their boundary is in danger of collapsing because of the site excavations. Plus the narrow rear laneway is making access a nightmare for materials and machinery. To cap off their woes, Sydney experiences its wettest summer in 20 years. Exhausted and three months behind schedule, do Brett and Rees have enough grit and determination left in them to see their project through?(n)
